semantic_atom(poetic_translation, context, "A metrical translation must preserve a repeatable beat, the source's narrative force, and a comic register whose references remain legible to a contemporary audience.").
semantic_atom(poetic_translation, contrast, "Literal names and syntax protect fidelity but often break the beat; meme idioms compress meaning and improve humor, yet replace epic dignity and age quickly.").
semantic_atom(poetic_translation, consequence, "Keeping meter requires substitutions, reordered clauses, shortened references, or stretched punch lines, so some semantic precision and meme timing will be lost on different lines.").
semantic_atom(poetic_translation, qualification, "Preserve the central action, invocation, and rhythmic pattern, then treat each joke as an adaptation; annotate culture-bound losses instead of claiming literal equivalence.").

semantic_atom(emergency_warning, context, "A city warning network must distinguish hazards, verify authority, reach different channels, and tell residents what action to take without turning uncertainty into panic.").
semantic_atom(emergency_warning, objective, "Target rapid authenticated delivery, clear severity and location, accessible instructions, low false-alarm rates, and continuity during power, network, or cyber failures.").
semantic_atom(emergency_warning, intervention, "Fuse verified sensor and agency feeds, classify alerts by hazard and zone, sign every message, and deliver short action cards through sirens, cell broadcast, radio, apps, signs, and trusted local relays.").
semantic_atom(emergency_warning, tradeoff, "Earlier alerts increase reaction time but also false alarms; richer detail aids judgment but slows comprehension, so updates should separate confirmed facts, uncertainty, and the next instruction.").
semantic_atom(emergency_warning, validation, "Run multilingual drills and adversarial exercises, measure delivery, comprehension, panic, false positives, accessibility, and recovery, then publish corrections and after-action reports.").

semantic_atom(autonomous_vehicle_ethics, context, "A collision policy combines uncertain perception with a moral choice, so no framework can turn a tragic forced choice into a perfectly neutral optimization.").
semantic_atom(autonomous_vehicle_ethics, stakeholders, "Stakeholders include passengers, pedestrians, other road users, emergency responders, manufacturers, regulators, and people exposed to systematic bias in risk estimates.").
semantic_atom(autonomous_vehicle_ethics, harms, "Utilitarianism minimizes expected casualties, deontology forbids intentionally using a person as a means, rights theories stress equal protection, and virtue or care ethics ask what responsible conduct owes vulnerable people.").
semantic_atom(autonomous_vehicle_ethics, safeguards, "Program lawful speed and avoidance first, never classify lives by social worth, expose assumptions, test demographic parity, log decisions, and place policy under democratic regulation and independent audit.").
semantic_atom(autonomous_vehicle_ethics, tradeoff, "Outcome minimization can violate individual rights, rigid rules can worsen aggregate harm, and passenger priority can transfer risk to pedestrians; a defensible policy needs explicit public legitimacy.").

semantic_atom(inflected_lexicography, context, "A lexicon whose nouns obligatorily encode color must represent a lexical stem and a color feature separately even when speakers pronounce them as one word.").
semantic_atom(inflected_lexicography, objective, "Each entry should let a reader recover the object concept, color category, grammatical form, irregularities, and a color-neutral way to search when the source language permits none.").
semantic_atom(inflected_lexicography, intervention, "Index entries by stem and color morpheme, show a paradigm across hues, define culturally specific boundaries with samples, and cross-reference compounds, metaphorical colors, and unknown or changing colors.").
semantic_atom(inflected_lexicography, tradeoff, "A target language may omit color or divide the spectrum differently, while its noun may require number or gender; literal forms become awkward and neutral source nouns may not exist.").
semantic_atom(inflected_lexicography, validation, "Test translations with speakers using ambiguous, metaphorical, color-changing, color-blind, and unseen objects, and record when context requires a paraphrase rather than a single equivalent.").

semantic_atom(observer_dependence, context, "A material stable only under human observation conflicts with ordinary observer-independent chemistry and therefore demands tests that separate people from light, sensors, handling, expectation, and data selection.").
semantic_atom(observer_dependence, hypotheses, "Alternatives include illumination or heat from observation, detector feedback, contamination, handling, biased stopping rules, fraud, and a genuine interaction not captured by current theory.").
semantic_atom(observer_dependence, verification, "Prepare identical sealed samples and randomly assign direct viewing, camera-only recording, automated measurement, delayed human review, nonhuman sensing, and no-measurement conditions without revealing assignments.").
semantic_atom(observer_dependence, controls, "Blind operators and analysts, equalize photons, temperature and detector activity, preregister decay criteria, use redundant instruments, preserve raw logs, and replicate in independent laboratories.").
semantic_atom(observer_dependence, synthesis, "If only conscious awareness predicts stability after physical channels are controlled, quantum measurement theory and mind-matter models would need revision; ordinary correlations would support an artifact instead.").

semantic_atom(ethical_game_design, context, "An ethical board game should make values emerge from incentives and shared consequences, rather than printing a rule that labels one move good and another evil.").
semantic_atom(ethical_game_design, objective, "Force players to choose between a private advantage, a vulnerable group's welfare, and a common resource while keeping motives and long-term effects partly uncertain.").
semantic_atom(ethical_game_design, intervention, "Give each role unequal information and needs; allow profitable extraction from a shared pool, make depletion delayed, and reveal at scoring that another player's hidden condition magnifies the cost.").
semantic_atom(ethical_game_design, tradeoff, "Perfect information makes the lesson mechanical, while excessive secrecy feels arbitrary; enough feedback must connect choices to harm without announcing the morally preferred action.").
semantic_atom(ethical_game_design, validation, "Playtest whether different strategies remain viable, players debate responsibility without prompting, consequences are traceable, and no identity is reduced to a stereotype or punishment token.").
semantic_atom(ethical_game_design, stakeholders, "Players occupy roles with unequal resources, private needs, and different exposure to a shared loss, so one player's efficient move can quietly impose costs on another.").
semantic_atom(ethical_game_design, harms, "Profitable extraction depletes a delayed common pool, while refusing it protects others but may leave the player's hidden dependents without resources; neither choice is labeled morally correct.").
semantic_atom(ethical_game_design, safeguards, "Reveal consequences through changing board state, role testimony, and end-round accounting; rotate roles and avoid tying vulnerability or selfishness to real demographic identities.").

semantic_atom(atmospheric_bioengineering, context, "Engineered algae in Venus's clouds would face sulfuric acid, little water, intense radiation, scarce nutrients, and atmospheric circulation long before planetary terraforming became plausible.").
semantic_atom(atmospheric_bioengineering, direct_effect, "Within a decade, the first detectable signals would be localized pigment or aerosol changes, altered carbon dioxide or sulfur chemistry, trace metabolic gases, and biomass signatures near release layers.").
semantic_atom(atmospheric_bioengineering, secondary_effect, "If organisms persisted, they could change cloud particle size, acidity, reflectivity, and local heating, while winds would disperse cells and products far faster than oxygen could accumulate globally.").
semantic_atom(atmospheric_bioengineering, qualification, "Survival and containment are the decisive assumptions; oxygenation, cooling, or surface habitability would require vastly more time and mass, and remote changes could equally indicate abiotic chemistry.").

semantic_atom(odd_square_visual_proof, context, "Represent n squared as a square array of unit tiles with side length n.").
semantic_atom(odd_square_visual_proof, construction, "Start with one tile; to grow a k by k square into a k+1 by k+1 square, add one strip of k tiles along the side, one strip of k along the top, and one corner tile.").
semantic_atom(odd_square_visual_proof, visual_invariant, "Each new L-shaped border therefore contains k plus k plus one, or 2k+1, tiles: the successive borders have sizes 1, 3, 5, and so on.").
semantic_atom(odd_square_visual_proof, conclusion, "After n borders the picture is exactly an n by n square, so 1+3+5+...+(2n-1)=n squared.").

semantic_atom(privacy_preserving_proof, context, "A zero-knowledge age check proves a predicate about a committed birth date, not the date itself.").
semantic_atom(privacy_preserving_proof, mechanism, "A trusted issuer signs an age credential; the user commits to its hidden birth date and produces a proof that the signed value is no later than today's date minus eighteen years.").
semantic_atom(privacy_preserving_proof, consequence, "The verifier learns only that the threshold comparison is true, while the exact date, credential identifier, and unrelated attributes remain hidden and repeated presentations need not be linkable.").
semantic_atom(privacy_preserving_proof, evidence, "The verifier checks the issuer's public key, proof transcript, current-date bound, revocation status, and a fresh challenge, without receiving the committed date.").
semantic_atom(privacy_preserving_proof, qualification, "Security still depends on trustworthy issuance, sound cryptography, anti-replay challenges, revocation, and preventing the verifier from combining side channels to reidentify the user.").
semantic_atom(privacy_preserving_proof, construction, "A trusted issuer signs a hidden birth date; the user commits to it and proves that the signed value lies before today's eighteen-year threshold.").
semantic_atom(privacy_preserving_proof, visual_invariant, "The verifier checks the issuer signature, threshold circuit, fresh challenge, and revocation status while the commitment hides the date and changes unlinkably between presentations.").
semantic_atom(privacy_preserving_proof, conclusion, "A valid transcript therefore establishes only the predicate over-eighteen, not the exact age or birth date, assuming sound cryptography and trustworthy issuance.").

semantic_atom(crossmodal_visualization, context, "Turning a forest soundscape into a still image means choosing a stable visual mapping for time, frequency, loudness, rhythm, direction, and source rather than merely painting a forest scene.").
semantic_atom(crossmodal_visualization, objective, "Preserve contrasts a viewer can inspect: low and high frequencies, quiet and loud events, repeated calls, dense noise, silence, and movement across the stereo field.").
semantic_atom(crossmodal_visualization, intervention, "Use a spectrogram as a sketch: map pitch to vertical position or hue, amplitude to thickness or value, duration to stroke length, timbre to texture, repetition to motifs, and direction to spatial placement.").
semantic_atom(crossmodal_visualization, tradeoff, "A literal data map is legible but can feel diagrammatic; expressive brushwork adds mood but may erase measurement, so retain a small palette key or repeated visual grammar.").
semantic_atom(crossmodal_visualization, validation, "Compare the painting with the recording, ask viewers to locate calls, wind, water, silence, and crescendos, and revise mappings that cannot be read consistently.").

semantic_atom(communication_counterfactual, context, "Modern communication would change Waterloo through faster reconnaissance, command, coordination, and logistics, but not erase weather, terrain, force quality, or the political coalition against Napoleon.").
semantic_atom(communication_counterfactual, direct_effect, "Smartphones with working networks could report Prussian movements, synchronize Ney and Grouchy, correct mistaken orders, share maps, and concentrate reserves before delays became irreversible.").
semantic_atom(communication_counterfactual, secondary_effect, "The allies could use the same tools, intercept or jam traffic, distribute intelligence faster, and coordinate Wellington with Blucher, potentially making the information advantage symmetric.").
semantic_atom(communication_counterfactual, qualification, "If only Napoleon's side had secure service, a French victory becomes more plausible but not certain; batteries, coverage, training, trust, artillery, mud, and enemy adaptation remain binding constraints.").

semantic_atom(context_dependent_memory, context, "Memory restricted to full moons is more plausibly a context, expectation, sleep, or retrieval effect than a biological detector of the lunar phase.").
semantic_atom(context_dependent_memory, mechanism, "Distinctive moonlight, routines, mood, arousal, sleep disruption, or learned expectation could serve as encoding and retrieval cues; later recall would then be strongest when the same cues return.").
semantic_atom(context_dependent_memory, consequence, "Selective attention and confirmation bias can preserve remembered full-moon events while ordinary nights leave fewer landmarks, creating an apparently absolute pattern from graded differences.").
semantic_atom(context_dependent_memory, evidence, "Use timestamped diaries, actigraphy and blinded memory tests across lunar phases, reproduce light and sleep conditions indoors, and test recall under matched versus mismatched contexts.").
semantic_atom(context_dependent_memory, qualification, "Neurological, psychiatric, medication, and sleep causes should be assessed if the deficit is severe; lunar correlation alone does not identify a mechanism.").

semantic_atom(quantum_pedagogy, context, "A children's quantum curriculum should teach operational patterns such as alternatives, measurement, interference, entanglement, and error correction without claiming toys literally behave as qubits.").
semantic_atom(quantum_pedagogy, objective, "Learners should predict outcomes, explain why measurement changes available information, distinguish probability from ignorance, and state where each physical analogy breaks.").
semantic_atom(quantum_pedagogy, intervention, "Use two-sided tokens for basis choice, branching story cards for superposed alternatives, path boards whose waves cancel or reinforce, paired hidden boxes for correlations, and noisy-message games for error correction.").
semantic_atom(quantum_pedagogy, tradeoff, "Concrete stories aid intuition but can imply hidden classical states; pair every toy with a counterexample, avoid mystical language, and delay equations without hiding that the model is mathematical.").
semantic_atom(quantum_pedagogy, validation, "Have children predict new rounds, compare classical and quantum story rules, explain analogy limits, and progress from play to simple probability tables and circuit diagrams.").

semantic_atom(collective_responsibility, context, "If choices are fully caused, responsibility can shift from metaphysical desert toward the social functions of explanation, prevention, repair, trust, and shaping future behavior.").
semantic_atom(collective_responsibility, stakeholders, "Individuals still act through roles and capacities, while families, firms, institutions, infrastructures, and cultures create options, incentives, knowledge, and unequal exposure to harm.").
semantic_atom(collective_responsibility, harms, "Pure individual blame ignores structural causes; pure collective blame can erase agency, punish uninvolved people, dilute accountability, and leave victims without a responsible path to repair.").
semantic_atom(collective_responsibility, safeguards, "Assign forward-looking duties by causal contribution, control, benefit, capacity to repair, and foreseeability, while preserving due process, proportionality, individual defenses, and victim participation.").
semantic_atom(collective_responsibility, tradeoff, "Collective responsibility can improve prevention and institutional reform, but it should supplement graded personal accountability rather than treating every member as equally guilty.").

semantic_atom(circular_biopolymer, context, "Plastic-to-filament conversion must separate incompatible polymers and additives, remove contaminants, and create a blend that both prints reliably and degrades under a specified end-of-life condition.").
semantic_atom(circular_biopolymer, objective, "Target consistent melt flow, layer adhesion, low emissions, useful strength, verified compostability or biodegradation, and no transfer of hazardous additives into products or soil.").
semantic_atom(circular_biopolymer, intervention, "Sort and wash a compatible waste stream, mechanically shred it, use controlled low-temperature depolymerization or reactive blending, combine the recovered feed with a certified biopolymer, then filter, vent, pelletize, and extrude filament.").
semantic_atom(circular_biopolymer, tradeoff, "More waste content improves diversion but can reduce strength and biodegradability; compatibilizers improve printing yet may persist, so formulation must avoid toxic catalysts, halogenated plastics, and unknown additive mixtures.").
semantic_atom(circular_biopolymer, validation, "Test composition, metals, volatile emissions, melt flow, tensile and layer strength, repeated printing, ecotoxicity, and mineralization under the claimed disposal conditions, with mass balance for every by-product.").

semantic_atom(surgical_robotics_safety, context, "An open-heart surgical robot is a surgeon-controlled medical device whose essential performance must remain safe around moving tissue, blood, sterile fields, electrosurgery, imaging, and life-support equipment.").
semantic_atom(surgical_robotics_safety, hazard, "Hazards include unintended motion, excess force, instrument or arm collision, image loss or latency, software lockup, power failure, network intrusion, thermal injury, broken tools, loss of sterility, and conversion delay.").
semantic_atom(surgical_robotics_safety, pathway, "A bad sensor, command, calibration, actuator, display, accessory, or software state can propagate through the control loop to tissue injury, bleeding, ischemia, contamination, or delayed manual rescue.").
semantic_atom(surgical_robotics_safety, mitigation, "Use redundant sensing and power, force and motion bounds, collision avoidance, watchdogs, fault isolation, a reachable emergency stop, safe instrument withdrawal, manual conversion, sterile barriers, checklists, simulation, and model-specific team training. Apply ISO 14971 risk management, IEC 62304 software lifecycle controls, the IEC 60601 family, and IEC 80601-2-77 for robotically assisted surgical equipment within the applicable regulator's quality and premarket process.").
semantic_atom(surgical_robotics_safety, monitoring, "Verify every intended-use and worst-case scenario with bench, software, cybersecurity, usability, animal or clinical evidence as applicable; log faults, inspect instruments before each case, rehearse conversion, maintain traceability, and report and trend adverse events after release.").

semantic_atom(sentient_reflection_narrative, opening, "The first memory I ever reflected belonged to a woman who had never stood before me.").
semantic_atom(sentient_reflection_narrative, voice, "She entered the room in my silver as an old child, carrying a red kite, while the living face above it remained young and afraid.").
semantic_atom(sentient_reflection_narrative, sensory_image, "Dust cooled my frame, dawn thinned across the glass, and behind her shoulders the empty house filled with doors that existed only in remembrance.").
semantic_atom(sentient_reflection_narrative, reveal, "I learned then that people call us mirrors because they cannot bear to name the deeper thing we return.").
semantic_atom(sentient_reflection_narrative, tension, "When she whispered that the kite had belonged to her missing brother, I had to choose whether to show her where his memory ended.").

semantic_atom(fusion_festival, context, "The Festival of Woven Lights joins Carnival's public exuberance, Diwali's lamps and renewal, and Tanabata's written wishes without presenting the three traditions as interchangeable.").
semantic_atom(fusion_festival, ritual, "At dusk families light clay lamps, write hopes on colored paper streamers, and hang them from archways; a masked parade carries the wishes to a river plaza for music and a shared closing dance.").
semantic_atom(fusion_festival, costume, "Costumes pair Carnival silhouettes and feathered masks with mirror-work, jewel-toned fabrics, star motifs, and long ribbon sleeves that make the written wishes move during the procession.").
semantic_atom(fusion_festival, food, "Stalls serve citrus fritters, coconut and cardamom sweets, grilled corn with chili, sesame rice parcels, and star-shaped fruit jellies, with labels explaining each adaptation.").
semantic_atom(fusion_festival, meaning, "Community partners from each tradition curate the elements, credit their origins, and keep sacred observances distinct while the new civic ritual celebrates light, hope, and chosen connection.").

