semantic_atom(traffic_signal_control, context, "A traffic-light network is a constrained control problem over queues, arrivals, pedestrian phases, transit priority, spillback, travel time, stops, fuel use, and emissions.").
semantic_atom(traffic_signal_control, objective, "Minimize a weighted combination of person-delay, queue spillback, stops, bus delay, pedestrian wait, and measured emissions rather than optimizing vehicle speed alone.").
semantic_atom(traffic_signal_control, intervention, "Fuse loop, camera, bus and air-quality data; estimate queues; coordinate offsets into green waves; and use bounded adaptive or model-predictive control to change splits and cycles as demand moves.").
semantic_atom(traffic_signal_control, tradeoff, "Long green waves help one corridor but can trap cross streets, pedestrians, and buses; rapid adaptation cuts queues but can destabilize coordination or reward extra driving.").
semantic_atom(traffic_signal_control, validation, "Calibrate a microscopic simulation, compare fixed-time and adaptive plans in shadow mode, then pilot while measuring person-delay, stops, emissions, safety conflicts, equity, and failure fallback.").

semantic_atom(scientific_poetry, context, "A black-hole haiku has only three short lines, so one accurate physical relation should carry the science while image, sound and omission carry scale and awe.").
semantic_atom(scientific_poetry, contrast, "Images such as bent light, a silent rim and a dawn that cannot return evoke lensing and the event horizon; saying the hole sucks everything or is literally empty would buy drama with false physics.").
semantic_atom(scientific_poetry, consequence, "Compression requires leaving out equations, accretion and relativity, but a precise verb can preserve the core fact: light paths bend and nothing inside the horizon returns.").
semantic_atom(scientific_poetry, qualification, "Prefer one scientifically defensible metaphor and a clean 5-7-5 rhythm, then let ambiguity express the observer's feeling rather than changing what the black hole does.").

semantic_atom(generative_art_ethics, context, "Exhibiting AI-generated art raises questions about authorship, training data, consent, labor, attribution, environmental cost, curation, and whether visitors understand how the work was made.").
semantic_atom(generative_art_ethics, stakeholders, "Stakeholders include source artists, model builders, prompt authors, curators, audiences, cultural communities represented in the data, workers displaced or enabled, and institutions funding the exhibition.").
semantic_atom(generative_art_ethics, harms, "Unlicensed imitation can appropriate style and labor, misleading labels can inflate human authorship, biased data can stereotype communities, and scale can crowd out artists while obscuring provenance and energy use.").
semantic_atom(generative_art_ethics, safeguards, "Label the workflow and human decisions, document model and data provenance where possible, secure rights and consent, compensate contributors, audit stereotypes, offer artist responses, and preserve a challenge process.").
semantic_atom(generative_art_ethics, tradeoff, "Generative tools can widen participation and create new collaboration, but novelty does not erase duties of attribution, fair compensation, cultural respect, transparency, and accountable curation.").

semantic_atom(sarcasm_recognition, context, "Sarcasm is a mismatch among literal words, prosody, context, shared expectations, facial cues, and speaker history, so no single keyword or flat sentiment label is sufficient.").
semantic_atom(sarcasm_recognition, objective, "Predict calibrated probabilities for literal, sarcastic, teasing, and uncertain speech across speakers and cultures, while allowing the robot to ask rather than act on a weak inference.").
semantic_atom(sarcasm_recognition, intervention, "Train a multimodal model on consented audio, transcripts and context; combine pitch, timing, stress, laughter, sentiment reversal, discourse contradiction, and speaker baselines, then fine-tune from explicit corrections.").
semantic_atom(sarcasm_recognition, tradeoff, "Personalization improves accuracy but threatens privacy and overfits stereotypes; a global model travels better but misses relationships, dialects, deadpan delivery, disability, and culture.").
semantic_atom(sarcasm_recognition, validation, "Split tests by speaker and culture, include literal hard negatives, measure calibration and subgroup error, test adversarial phrasing, and make uncertain outputs trigger clarification instead of confident judgment.").

semantic_atom(consensual_healing_creature, context, "The velisyr is a moon-white, six-legged creature with translucent antlers and a warm crimson glow moving beneath feathered scales.").
semantic_atom(consensual_healing_creature, objective, "Its blood can close any wound, but healing works only when the velisyr freely offers a drop; blood taken by force turns inert and leaves a dark scar on the taker.").
semantic_atom(consensual_healing_creature, intervention, "It senses pain through its antlers, kneels only before someone it trusts, and places a voluntary tear of blood on the wound, where it becomes a branching red-gold seal.").
semantic_atom(consensual_healing_creature, tradeoff, "Kings try to imprison it, patients plead for impossible triage, and communities must earn trust while accepting that compassion cannot be extracted as a resource.").
semantic_atom(consensual_healing_creature, validation, "The premise makes consent observable through the failed stolen blood, gives the creature motives and limits, and turns every cure into a relationship and moral choice rather than unlimited magic.").

semantic_atom(direct_digital_democracy, context, "Direct mobile voting would shift lawmaking from periodic representation toward continuous mass participation mediated by identity systems, interfaces, platforms, and agenda-setting rules.").
semantic_atom(direct_digital_democracy, direct_effect, "Participation and responsiveness could rise, while voters face many technical questions, campaigns become continuous, representatives lose discretion, and secure access becomes part of citizenship.").
semantic_atom(direct_digital_democracy, secondary_effect, "Well-funded persuasion, misinformation, coercion, digital exclusion, shallow turnout, majority cycling, platform outages, and rushed reactions could grow; deliberative assemblies and delegated votes might also emerge.").
semantic_atom(direct_digital_democracy, qualification, "Consequences depend on authentication, secrecy, auditability, accessibility, agenda control, cooling-off periods, constitutional rights, expert review, and a non-digital channel, not on the app alone.").

semantic_atom(adaptive_coloration, context, "Chameleons and octopuses both change appearance through layered skin structures, but the cellular mechanisms and the speed and range of control differ.").
semantic_atom(adaptive_coloration, mechanism, "A chameleon actively rearranges reflective guanine nanocrystals in iridophore cells, changing which wavelengths are reflected, while pigment cells and deeper reflectors shape brightness and contrast.").
semantic_atom(adaptive_coloration, consequence, "An octopus uses neural signals to expand or contract pigment-filled chromatophore sacs in milliseconds, with iridophores, leucophores, papillae, and posture adding iridescence, whiteness, and texture.").
semantic_atom(adaptive_coloration, evidence, "Microscopy and optical spectra reveal changing crystal spacing in chameleons, whereas nerve stimulation and high-speed imaging show muscular chromatophore expansion and rapid patterned control in octopuses.").
semantic_atom(adaptive_coloration, qualification, "Chameleon change is generally slower and serves signaling and temperature as well as camouflage; octopus control is faster, neurally patterned, and can coordinate color, brightness, polarization, and skin texture.").

semantic_atom(contact_dialect_design, context, "Harbor English is a fictional contact dialect that keeps English vocabulary while borrowing topic-prominent discourse from Mandarin and agglutinative agreement and noun-class echoes from Swahili.").
semantic_atom(contact_dialect_design, objective, "The dialect needs a small consistent grammar, learnable sound changes, productive forms, and social variation rather than random foreign words or caricatured accents.").
semantic_atom(contact_dialect_design, intervention, "Put topics first with a pause, allow dropped subjects when context is clear, use invariant verbs plus aspect particles, and attach simplified noun-class prefixes that trigger matching agreement on adjectives and demonstratives.").
semantic_atom(contact_dialect_design, tradeoff, "Combining systems creates ambiguity when English tense, Mandarin aspect, and Swahili agreement compete; speakers would regularize the mix and preserve different forms by region, age, and identity.").
semantic_atom(contact_dialect_design, validation, "Test examples such as 'This book, I already read' and 'ki-book ki-new this' across statements, questions, negation and stories, then revise rules that speakers cannot extend to new words.").

semantic_atom(ancient_technology_transfer, context, "A useful gift to ancient Egypt must work without modern grids, replacement chips, industrial supply chains, or specialized fuels, and should be teachable from local materials.").
semantic_atom(ancient_technology_transfer, criteria, "Prioritize reproducibility, public benefit, low maintenance, safety, compatibility with existing crafts, and knowledge that can seed further invention rather than one impressive device that soon fails.").
semantic_atom(ancient_technology_transfer, options, "Candidates include a rugged printing press, optical microscope, improved water pump, germ-theory kit, or compact reference library with drawings and measurement standards.").
semantic_atom(ancient_technology_transfer, rationale, "Choose a simple movable-type press plus illustrated manuals: local artisans could copy and repair it, multiplying medical, mathematical, agricultural, and engineering knowledge across generations.").
semantic_atom(ancient_technology_transfer, caveat, "Literacy, script design, political control, papyrus supply, and elite resistance could limit impact, so training printers and distributing open copies matter as much as the machine.").

semantic_atom(tragedy_adaptation, context, "A modern Greek-tragedy adaptation should preserve the collision among duty, kinship, power, fate, and irreversible consequence while changing the social machinery that makes the conflict immediate now.").
semantic_atom(tragedy_adaptation, objective, "Keep the tragic choice, moral ambiguity, recognition, reversal, and communal witness, but make stakes legible without turning the chorus into a lecture or the ending into easy redemption.").
semantic_atom(tragedy_adaptation, intervention, "Move the conflict into a family, state, corporation, war, or climate emergency; translate formal speeches into heightened contemporary language; and recast the chorus as citizens, media, workers, or a live ensemble.").
semantic_atom(tragedy_adaptation, tradeoff, "Contemporary pacing and realism improve access but can shrink mythic scale; spectacle can overwhelm argument, while literal reverence can make living conflict feel like a museum piece.").
semantic_atom(tragedy_adaptation, validation, "Workshop whether audiences can name both sides' values, track the fatal choice and recognition, and feel the chorus's public pressure without prior knowledge of the source.").

semantic_atom(prophetic_photograph_narrative, opening, "The first photograph showed Mara standing beneath tomorrow's collapsed bridge, although she had taken it from her kitchen window.").
semantic_atom(prophetic_photograph_narrative, voice, "She blamed the old camera until the next print developed: her brother opening a letter that had not yet been written, his face already folding at its news.").
semantic_atom(prophetic_photograph_narrative, sensory_image, "Silver clouds crawled across the paper in the red darkroom light, and every image smelled of rain a day before the weather changed.").
semantic_atom(prophetic_photograph_narrative, reveal, "By noon she understood that the lens did not predict possibilities; it selected one future each time she pressed the shutter.").
semantic_atom(prophetic_photograph_narrative, tension, "Then the final photograph surfaced, showing her hand on the camera and no world at all beyond the frame.").

semantic_atom(dao_security, context, "A DAO can be captured through concentrated voting power, flash-loan governance, delegated keys, malicious proposals, compromised interfaces, treasury permissions, oracle attacks, or apathetic turnout.").
semantic_atom(dao_security, objective, "Protect proposal integrity and treasury safety while keeping governance contestable, transparent, recoverable, and resistant to both a sudden attacker and permanent insider control.").
semantic_atom(dao_security, intervention, "Use delayed execution, proposal bonds, quorum and supermajority rules, time-weighted or snapshot voting, delegation limits, multisignature guardians, scoped permissions, rate limits, audited code, and an emergency pause with sunset.").
semantic_atom(dao_security, tradeoff, "Higher quorums and long delays resist raids but entrench large holders and slow urgent fixes; guardians improve recovery but reintroduce trust and censorship risk.").
semantic_atom(dao_security, validation, "Simulate flash loans, bribery, key loss, oracle failure, low turnout, malicious upgrades and guardian abuse; publish invariants, monitor concentration, and rehearse transparent recovery before funding the treasury.").

semantic_atom(musical_steganography, context, "A symphonic secret can hide information in musical choices that sound motivated while a recipient with the key maps them back to symbols.").
semantic_atom(musical_steganography, objective, "The code should survive performance variation, avoid obvious statistical anomalies, fit the style, and include synchronization and error correction so one missed note does not destroy the message.").
semantic_atom(musical_steganography, intervention, "Map pitch classes, intervals, rhythms, dynamics, instrumentation, motif order, or chord inversions to bits or letters; use a recurring key motif as a header and distribute redundant fragments across sections.").
semantic_atom(musical_steganography, tradeoff, "Dense encoding increases capacity but constrains composition and becomes detectable; subtle low-rate coding preserves expression but is vulnerable to transposition, cuts, interpretation, and copying errors.").
semantic_atom(musical_steganography, validation, "Test decoding from score, rehearsal recording and varied performances, measure error rate after tempo and key changes, and compare pitch and rhythm statistics with unencoded music in the same style.").

semantic_atom(entanglement_communication, context, "Entanglement alone cannot carry a controllable message faster than light, because each local measurement is random; security comes from correlations plus an authenticated classical channel.").
semantic_atom(entanglement_communication, direct_effect, "Entanglement-based quantum key distribution lets two parties measure paired systems in chosen bases, compare a sample publicly, and derive shared random key bits when correlations match quantum predictions.").
semantic_atom(entanglement_communication, secondary_effect, "Eavesdropping or untrusted sources disturb correlations and raise the error rate; Bell-test or device-independent variants can reduce trust in hardware, but loss, distance, side channels, and authentication remain practical limits.").
semantic_atom(entanglement_communication, qualification, "The result is not a magical secure data channel: privacy amplification and error correction produce a key, conventional authenticated encryption carries the message, and endpoint compromise still defeats it.").
semantic_atom(entanglement_communication, objective, "Use quantum correlations to establish a shared key with detectable eavesdropping, while preserving authentication, availability, endpoint security, and an explicit abort threshold.").
semantic_atom(entanglement_communication, intervention, "Distribute entangled photon pairs, choose measurement bases independently, reveal a random sample over an authenticated classical link, estimate errors or a Bell violation, then apply error correction and privacy amplification.").
semantic_atom(entanglement_communication, tradeoff, "Stronger device independence reduces hardware trust but demands higher detection efficiency and lower loss; repeaters extend distance but add immature memories and interfaces, and no design removes denial-of-service risk.").
semantic_atom(entanglement_communication, validation, "Measure key rate, quantum bit error, loss, finite-key security, detector side channels and authentication failure under attacks, and prove that excess disturbance causes abort before using the key.").

semantic_atom(ecosystem_board_game, context, "In Canopy Commons, players cooperatively build a food web from habitat, plant, herbivore, predator, decomposer, water, soil, and energy tiles while each also manages a private community goal.").
semantic_atom(ecosystem_board_game, objective, "Win by keeping biodiversity, nutrient cycling, water and population balance above thresholds through four seasons; everyone loses if resilience or any essential trophic layer collapses.").
semantic_atom(ecosystem_board_game, intervention, "Each turn adds or restores one link, spends limited energy, and draws a disaster such as drought, fire, flood, disease or invasive species whose effect propagates along the visible food web.").
semantic_atom(ecosystem_board_game, tradeoff, "Specialization scores quickly but creates brittle dependencies; redundancy costs resources yet absorbs shocks, and private objectives tempt players to externalize risk onto the shared ecosystem.").
semantic_atom(ecosystem_board_game, validation, "Playtest that multiple webs can survive, disaster randomness never decides alone, causal cascades are readable, cooperation matters without one dominant player, and ecological strategies match the represented links.").

semantic_atom(postscarcity_aesthetics, context, "Post-scarcity removes much material necessity but not mortality, attention, curiosity, embodiment, memory, disagreement, identity, play, or the need to interpret shared experience.").
semantic_atom(postscarcity_aesthetics, premise, "Art can be justified intrinsically as perception and expression, instrumentally as exploration and communication, socially as ritual and criticism, and politically as a way to imagine alternatives even without markets.").
semantic_atom(postscarcity_aesthetics, technique, "A philosophical case can draw on play, aesthetic experience, self-creation, collective memory, estrangement, meaning-making, and the public testing of values rather than on scarcity or employment alone.").
semantic_atom(postscarcity_aesthetics, tension, "Abundance may end patronage and survival pressure while intensifying competition for attention, authenticity, recognition, novelty, and access to culturally important spaces.").
semantic_atom(postscarcity_aesthetics, implication, "Art would not need to justify its existence as a commodity; it would remain one way finite beings choose what to notice, share possible worlds, and make freedom intelligible.").

semantic_atom(desert_wheat_editing, context, "Creating desert-adapted wheat is a multi-trait breeding problem involving water use, roots, stomata, heat, salinity, flowering time, grain yield, disease, and local soils, not one drought gene.").
semantic_atom(desert_wheat_editing, mechanism, "Select validated regulatory or coding targets, use CRISPR to alter native alleles controlling deeper roots, stomatal response, osmotic protection, wax, salt transport or heat tolerance, and regenerate independently edited lines.").
semantic_atom(desert_wheat_editing, consequence, "Edits may reduce water loss and protect cells but can slow photosynthesis, growth or yield; pyramiding small changes and crossing them into adapted cultivars can balance survival with harvest.").
semantic_atom(desert_wheat_editing, evidence, "Sequence on- and off-target sites, compare edited and control plants under staged drought, heat and salinity, then run multi-season field trials measuring water use, yield, grain quality, disease and ecological effects.").
semantic_atom(desert_wheat_editing, qualification, "Field success also needs soil management, irrigation strategy, farmer access, seed diversity, biosafety review, and testing across environments because greenhouse tolerance may not survive real deserts.").
